e>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 45<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(3/26/02 6:41:46 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=481.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Evolution of language</span><hr size=1> Kzan,<br><br>That's my point (though I think I should have phrased is a little clearer).  Equal rights for women and minorities are just one example of exactly what I mean.  In the past, they were non-existent, because society said so.  However, does that mean that the oppression was ok, because it was socially acceptable?  I would say no, and if society for some reason decided once again women shouldn't have equal rights, it would still be equally wrong regardless of what society says.  If not, then we have no right to say other countries are wrong for suppressing religious-freedom, free-speech, sexual, gender, racial, or other rights.  It's clearly what that society says is ok, so we should just butt out and let them do whatever they want.<br><br>&quot;All it takes for evil to triumph, is a good man to do nothing.&quot;<br><br>A more extreme example, multiple societies in the past have tried to justify the killing of innocents, and this continues today.  Because it's acceptable in the society, does that make it right?  Were the Inquisitor's right in torturing and killing &quot;heretics&quot; because society at the time ok'd it?  Nazi Germany killing the Jews?  The murder of a million armenians?  The ongoing massacre in Sudan?  It does not matter if the society tried/tries to deem them acceptable for whatever reason, the killing of innocents is not now, and has never been, right.  <br><br>Oppression is never right, regardless of society's view.  Killing of innocents is never right, regardless of society's view.  There are such things as right and wrong, regardless of the spin post-modernism tries to put on things.  <br><br>One last thing, in the thread that gave rise to this, someone made the comment on having a &quot;debate between people with open-minds.&quot;  There is no such thing as a person with an open-mind, because whenever anyone says this, it can correctly be translated as &quot;you're open-minded as long as after talking to me you come to agree with me, and if you don't, you're a bigot and narrow-minded.&quot;  There is no such thing as an open-minded discussion...<br><br>End rant, because I'd rather play than argue <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br><br>Jaelyn <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ujaelyndimathe.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Jaelyn DiMathe</A> at: 3/27/02 12:35:21 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ukimayasilverbark.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Kimaya Silverbark</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://prod.bsis.bellsouth.net/coDataImages/bellsouthpwp/Groups/15/15568/folders/6507/Thumbnails/67125button-wolf-pawprint" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 37<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(3/26/02 9:35:12 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=481.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.bellsouth.net/coDataImages/bellsouthpwp/Groups/15/15568/pages/34736/Kimaya-60.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   My Philosophy</span><hr size=1> Wrong = Hurting people when it can be reasonably avoided<br>Right = Avoiding hurting people when it can be reasonably avoided<br><br>What's reasonable?  What's taking things too far?  When is someone getting hurt NOT a direct result of what's being done, but is rather more a result of something unavoidable?<br><br>*shrug*  If we could all agree on that, we wouldn't have to debate whether a word, or even an action, has &quot;evolved beyond its hurtful roots&quot;, or is still simply &quot;hurtful&quot;. <p><p align="center"><img src="http://prod.bsis.bellsouth.net/coDataImages/bellsouthpwp/Groups/15/15568/folders/6507/73377kimaya-sig.gif" width="381" height="100"><br><a href="http://home.bellsouth.net/personalpages/PWP-TwilightBastion"><i>~ Click here to visit the Bastion ~</i></a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ujarkellraven.showPublicProfile?language=EN>JarkellRaven</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 94<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(3/27/02 12:00:12 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=481.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: My Philosophy</span><hr size=1> I don't know about anyone else, but I'm Jewish, and I'd get real pissed if anyone said &quot;Jewed&quot; out of anything around me.  If they didn't appologize, I'd &quot;Jew&quot; them onto the floor with a nice right hook. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uhenkoffv.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Henk of FV</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 45<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(3/27/02 12:02:18 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=481.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: My Philosophy</span><hr size=1> I agree with the point that Elizer is trying to make: getting offended at something that is not meant to be harmful is a waste of good anger.<br><br>On the other side, however, if you find yourself wondering whether someone is going to have to parse out your context to avoid an insult, perhaps it would be better not to use the language in the first place.<br><br>“Jewed” is still considered derogatory in most polite society, and it’s a terms that has been around for half a millennia.  “Kiked” is likewise offensive.<br><br>“Gyp” is a word whose origins are actually lost; presuming it is short for “Gypsy” is the popular assumption, but since the word has North American origins, that may not be correct.<br><br>A couple years back, the president of the NAACP used the term “niggardly” (adj: stingy, miserly) and was buried under criticism from the African-American community, even though he had done absolutely nothing but use a terms whose roots are from Middle English and which has absolutely no connection to the… ahem… “N-word”.  He apologized – as he should have:  He did nothing wrong, but using a near-homophone of a certain term was unwise in the discussion he was engage in. <br><br>I use the “thumbs up” signal to indicate that I am pleased with something.  There are countries where that gesture has a very different connotation.  Since I do not particularly want to offend the natives of those countries, I try not to use it there.<br><br>As with all things: moderation.  If you find yourself using a term that a significant population finds offensive, you may want to stop.  <br> <p>----------------------------<br>-Henk<br>Grumpy Cleric of Brell<br></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ujuinfalconer.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Juin Falconer</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 21<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(3/27/02 5:43:01 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=481.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> 